INTRODUCTION

This is an analysis of the worldwide venture capital fund allocation. I visualized the data with some plots, mainly using ggplot2.

I drawed a small sample of the 5 market leaders from the data and then carried out some hypothesis testing between the two variables: funding_total_usd and market

First, let’s attach the packages to help generate the graphs
library(tidyverse)
library(ggplot2)
library(scales)
library(rmarkdown)
Read in data and ommit NA
vc_fund<- read.csv("investments_VC.csv")
vc_Fund <- na.omit(vc_fund)
attach(vc_Fund)

Interestingly, the number of new startups has been rising ever since 2000. The peak period is between 2010 and 2015 with 2012 having more than 5000 new startups.

Also, the percentage of successful startup at 95% (which includes both acquired and operating) are suprisingly much greater than the percentage of failed startup.

Generate a sample of top 5 leading market leaders and their funding total in USD
detach()
sample_top5_funding_total<- subset(vc_Fund, market ==" Biotechnology " | market ==" Software " |
                            market ==" Mobile " 
                          | market==" E-Commerce " | market==" Curated Web ", 
                          select=c(market, funding_total_usd))
sample_top5_funding_total2<-subset(sample_top5_funding_total, funding_total_usd!=" NA   ")
sample_top5_funding_total2$funding_total_usd<-as.numeric(gsub(",", "", sample_top5_funding_total2$funding_total_usd))
ANOVA Testing

H0: mean(software)=mean(mobile)=mean(biotechnology)=mean(curated web)=mean(ecommerce)

H1: at least one of the means is different

total_lm <- lm(funding_total_usd~market, data=sample_top5_funding_total2)
anova(total_lm)
## Analysis of Variance Table
## 
## Response: funding_total_usd
##             Df     Sum Sq    Mean Sq F value Pr(>F)
## market       4 6.5841e+17 1.6460e+17  1.6606 0.1561
## Residuals 9365 9.2830e+20 9.9124e+16

The p-value is 0.1561
Decision: Since the p-value is greater than 0.1, we fail to reject the null hypothesis

Conclusion: There is no evidence that the mean funding total of the five market leader are different

To confirm this finding, we will go ahead and do a pair-wise t test
pairwise.t.test(funding_total_usd, market, "bonferroni")
## 
##  Pairwise comparisons using t tests with pooled SD 
## 
## data:  funding_total_usd and market 
## 
##                Biotechnology   Curated Web   E-Commerce   Mobile 
##  Curated Web  1.00            -             -            -       
##  E-Commerce   1.00            1.00          -            -       
##  Mobile       1.00            0.41          1.00         -       
##  Software     1.00            1.00          1.00         0.29    
## 
## P value adjustment method: bonferroni

The values we get from the test table concur with the findings we got from the ANOVA test. The total funding mean between the top 5 setors are not much different from each other. There are some evidence that the mean total funding of mobile are different than the mean funding of Curated Web and Software

These findings makes sense considering the notable diffrence in capital structure and need of the mobile industry versus other industry

Let’s count the number of startups for each market leaders
market_table = sort(table(market), decreasing = TRUE)
head(market_table, n=5)
## market
##       Software   Biotechnology          Mobile      E-Commerce  
##            3327            2373            1402            1175 
##    Curated Web  
##            1093
Are the proportions of these different markets the same? Let’s test the hypothesises using Chi-square Goodness-of-fit.

H0: The proportions are the same

H1: The proportions varies and different from each other

top_5_count <- c(3327,2373,1402,1175,1093)
chisq.test(top_5_count, correct = FALSE)
## 
##  Chi-squared test for given probabilities
## 
## data:  top_5_count
## X-squared = 1964.5, df = 4, p-value < 2.2e-16

Decision: Since the p-value is very small, we reject the null hypothesis

Conclusion: There is strong evidence that the proportion of the each of top 5 market leaders are not equal
